pd_0_com_1text: Lord Zeppelin was a very educated man with an enviable collection of books.
pd_0_com_2text: But as I know him, there must be more behind this bookshelf than it seems at first glance.
pd_0_com_3text: Maybe if I push the right book or order the books differently somehow?
pd_0_com_5text: Ah, there you go. A secret compartment.
pd_1_com_0text: The key fits perfectly into the lock.
pd_1_com_1text: I wonder what's inside that secret compartment.
pd_1_com_2text: Hmm... Cash, jewellery, probably family heirlooms, awards and documents.
pd_1_com_3text: The other stuff won't help me with my investigation, but the documents will!
pd_1_com_4text: I have a draft of a new will here.
pd_1_com_5text: Apparently Lord Zeppelin had decided to donate almost all his wealth after his death.
pd_1_com_6text: Lady hot-air balloon would have almost nothing with this.
pd_1_com_7text: However, the will is not signed and therefore not legally valid.
pd_1_com_8text: Did Lady Hot Air Balloon murder Lord Zeppelin to prevent him from changing his will?
pd_2_com_0text: But this document is not negligible either.
pd_2_com_1text: It proves that the general has evaded large sums of money in taxes in recent years.
pd_2_com_2text: I'm sure the general wouldn't be happy if this went public.
pd_3_com_0text: Maybe Lord Zeppelin wasn't willing to cover up the General's fraud and that's why the General murdered him?
pd_4_com_0text: This must be the document the General so desperately searched for in the Lord's study.
pd_5_com_0text: I am sure that one of these two documents has become the Lord's doom, but which one?
pd_6_com_0text: The secret compartment is locked. I don't want to break it open.
pd_6_com_1text: I'm sure Lord Zeppelin has hidden the key to it somewhere around here.
pd_6_com_2text: Perhaps I should look for the key.
